dth=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"300\" y2=\"330\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <circle cx=\"300\" cy=\"170\" r=\"148\" transform=\"scale(-1 1) translate(-600 0)  rotate(180 300 170)\"></circle> <line class=\"radius-line\" x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"448\" y2=\"169\"></line> <line class=\"vertical45\" x1=\"448\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"506\" y2=\"169\"></line> <line class=\"radius-45\" x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"406\" y2=\"66\"></line>  <line class=\"vertical45\" x1=\"406\" y1=\"66\" x2=\"406\" y2=\"166\"></line> <line class=\"vertical45\" x1=\"407\" y1=\"65\" x2=\"508\" y2=\"168\"></line> <line class=\"vertical45\" x1=\"302\" y1=\"65\" x2=\"400\" y2=\"65\"></line> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"330\" y=\"118\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">1</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"470\" y=\"118\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">tan θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"320\" y=\"60\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">cos θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"420\" y=\"128\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\" text-anchor=\"middle\" dominant-baseline=\"central\" transform=\"rotate(90, 420, 128)\">sen θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"320\" y=\"165\" font-size=\"1.0em\" font-weight=\"bold\">θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"282\" y=\"187\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">O</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"282\" y=\"9\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">y</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"407\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">P</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"370\" y=\"187\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">sec θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"500\" y=\"187\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">R</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"520\" y=\"190\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">x</text></svg></div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 1</b>: Circle showing trigonometric relationships.</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "### The other hypotenuse\n\nIn this text, we will focus on the secant line illustrated in **Graph 1** and understand what we can expect from the values of this function in the first quadrant we are studying.\n\n#### Isolating\n\nIn order to make what we are analyzing in this text more visible, we will isolate from Graph 1 the parts necessary for this study:",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<div class=\"atlasCircleContainer\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 600 200\" class=\"circle-draw\" id=\"svgcirctri0\">  <defs> <marker id=\"arrow\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"3\" markerHeight=\"3\" orient=\"auto-start-reverse\"> <path d=\"M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z\" /></marker></defs>  <line class=\"radius-line\" x1=\"200\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"348\" y2=\"169\"></line> <line class=\"vertical45\" x1=\"348\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"406\" y2=\"169\"></line> <line class=\"radius-45\" x1=\"200\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"306\" y2=\"66\"></line>  <line class=\"vertical45\" x1=\"307\" y1=\"65\" x2=\"408\" y2=\"168\"></line> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"230\" y=\"118\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">1</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"370\" y=\"118\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">tan θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"220\" y=\"165\" font-size=\"1.0em\" font-weight=\"bold\">θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"182\" y=\"187\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">O</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"307\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">P</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"285\" y=\"187\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">sec θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"400\" y=\"187\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">R</text> </svg></div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 2</b>: Triangle from <b>Graph 1</b> showing the secant as the hypotenuse of the triangle.</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The definition\n\nThe secant line we see in **Graph 2** was also defined mathematically when we were manipulating trigonometric relationships, from which we concluded that the secant function is defined as (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "213a8932-84c2-4f72-9852-38368994d9a5",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Did we tangent the planet?",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\" style=\"background-color: #FFFFFF;\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\" style=\"background-color: #FFFFFF;\"><p><math mathsize=\"1.5em\" displaystyle=\"false\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mi>sec (θ)</mi><mn>=</mn><mfrac><mi>1</mi><mi>cos (θ)</mi></mfrac></math></p> <p class=\"desc\"><b>Formula 1</b>: Definition of the secant.</p></div></div></center>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Curiosity\n\nDespite our knowledge of the function, an important point raised by Eric W. Weisstein is worth highlighting. This function had its origin practically alongside the tangent; however, when another mathematical function—the logarithm—was discovered, its use was reduced (<htcite0>).\n\n#### Graph\n\nWe can understand the graph of the secant function from the tangent graph itself shown on the previous page (<htcite1>). In it, we learned that the tangent is given by dividing the sine function by the cosine function (**Formula 2**):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "603c44f8-9b51-44f3-a538-9ddc6ba7be05",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Secant",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "cbce5f98-ad82-4995-b5f0-960554919dbd",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Our position",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\" style=\"background-color: #FFFFFF;\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\" style=\"background-color: #FFFFFF;\"><p><math mathsize=\"1.5em\" displaystyle=\"false\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mi>tan (θ)</mi><mn>=</mn><mfrac><mi>sen(θ)</mi><mi>cos (θ)</mi></mfrac></math></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Formula 2</b>: Definition of tangent according to trigonometric functions.</p></div></div></center>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "By comparing **Formulas 1 and 2**, we can observe that both have cosine theta in the denominator, but in **Formula 1**, we have a constant value in the numerator. From this, we can expect from the graph:\n- When cosine theta (θ) has its greatest value, 1, then the value of the secant will be equal to 1;\n- As seen in another text from History Tracers, between 0 and 1 there are infinite numbers (<htcite0>). As the cosine value starts at its maximum value and decreases toward zero, the secant value will begin to grow as we approach zero;\n- There is no secant value when the cosine value is equal to zero.\n\nTo better understand what we have described, see **Graph 3**:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d06e24cb-52e8-4ff8-ae37-12052c91b187",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Limiting",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chartsec1\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 3</b>: Graph of the secant function. Graph created with the <htcite0> library.</div></p><script> htPlotSecant('chartsec1', 'teta (radianos)', 'secante (θ)', 1);</script>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9",
                     "text": "Chart JS",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "05",
                        "day": "30"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "To aid in comparison with the tangent graph, we draw it again below:",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"charttan2\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 4</b>: Graph of the tangent function. Graph created with the <htcite0> library.</div></p><script> htPlotTan('charttan2', 1);</script>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9",
                     "text": "Chart JS",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "05",
                        "day": "30"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### From one graph to the other\n\n**Graph 1** shows us the secant in an intermediate position. Thus, we will adjust this graph to the extremes, so that we can understand the values that appear in **Graph 3**.\n\nFirst, we will start with the scenario in which cosine theta reaches its greatest value and, consequently, secant theta has its smallest value:",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
